# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: segment-tree
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:segment-tree/fenwick-tree] A **Fenwick tree** or **binary indexed tree** **(BIT)** is a data structure that stores an array of values and can efficiently compute prefix sums of the values *and* update the values.
[src:segment-tree/fenwick-tree] It also supports an efficient rank-search operation for finding the longest prefix whose sum is no more than a specified value.
[src:segment-tree/fenwick-tree] Its primary use is operating on the cumulative distribution function of a statistical frequency table which is updated often.
[src:segment-tree/fenwick-tree] This structure was proposed by Boris Ryabko in 1989 with a further modification published in 1992.
[src:segment-tree/fenwick-tree] It has subsequently become known under the name Fenwick tree after Peter Fenwick, who described this structure in his 1994 article.
[src:segment-tree/fenwick-tree] A simple array of values is trivial (constant-time) to update but requires $O(n)$ time to compute a prefix sum or search for a prefix length.
[src:segment-tree/fenwick-tree] An array of prefix sums can return a prefix sum in constant time, and search for a prefix length in $O(\log n)$ time, but requires $O(n)$ time to update one of the values.
[src:segment-tree/fenwick-tree] A Fenwick tree allows all three operations to be performed in $O(\log n)$ time.
[src:segment-tree/fenwick-tree] This is achieved by representing the values as a tree with $n+1$ nodes where each node in the tree stores the sum of the values from the index of its parent (exclusive) up to the index of the node (inclusive).
[src:segment-tree/fenwick-tree] The tree itself is implicit and can be stored as an array of n values, with the implicit root node omitted from the array.
[src:segment-tree/fenwick-tree] The tree structure allows the operations of value retrieval, value update, prefix sum, and range sum to be performed using only $O(\log n)$ node accesses.
[src:segment-tree/fenwick-tree] Given an array of values, it is sometimes desirable to calculate the running total of values up to each index according to some associative binary operation (addition on integers being by far the most common).
[src:segment-tree/fenwick-tree] Fenwick trees provide a method to query the running total at any index, or prefix sum, while allowing changes to the underlying value array and having all further queries reflect those changes.
[src:segment-tree/fenwick-tree] Fenwick trees are particularly designed to implement adaptive arithmetic coding, which maintains counts of each symbol produced and needs to convert those to the cumulative probability of a symbol less than a given symbol.
[src:segment-tree/fenwick-tree] Development of operations it supports were primarily motivated by use in that case.
[src:segment-tree/fenwick-tree] A Fenwick tree is an implicit tree where nodes are consecutively numbered, and parent-child relationships are determined by arithmetic on the node indexes.
[src:segment-tree/fenwick-tree] An important function in this index arithmetic is the *least significant set bit*.
[src:segment-tree/fenwick-tree] This is the greatest power of two which divides an index i .
[src:segment-tree/fenwick-tree] It can be efficiently computed in two's complement arithmetic as $\operatorname {lsb} (i)=i\mathbin {\&} -i$ (where & denotes bitwise AND).
[src:segment-tree/fenwick-tree] A Fenwick tree is most easily understood using a one-based array $A[n]$ with n values.
[src:segment-tree/fenwick-tree] Using half-open interval syntax, let $A(i,j]=\{A[k]\}_{k=i+1}^{j},$ the range from i (exclusive) to j (inclusive).
[src:segment-tree/fenwick-tree] The corresponding Fenwick array $F[n]$ stores the range sums $\textstyle F[i]=\sum A(i-\operatorname {lsb} (i),i]$ .
[src:segment-tree/fenwick-tree] That is, the sum of $\operatorname {lsb} (i)$ values ending with and including $A[i]$ .
[src:segment-tree/fenwick-tree] A fictitious node 0 is used in some descriptions, but is never actually accessed and need not be explicitly stored. $\operatorname {lsb} (0)=\infty ,$ but the value is never actually needed. $F[0]$ may be considered to contain the sum of the empty range $A(0,0]=\{\}$ with value 0.
[src:segment-tree/fenwick-tree] A "Fenwick tree" is actually *three* implicit trees over the same array: the *interrogation tree* used for translating indexes to prefix sums, the *update* tree used for updating elements, and the *search tree* for translating prefix sums to indexes (rank queries).
[src:segment-tree/fenwick-tree] The first two are normally walked upwards, while the third is usually walked downwards.
[src:segment-tree/fenwick-tree] The interrogation tree is defined so that the parent of node i is $i-\operatorname {lsb} (i)=i\mathbin {\&} (i-1)$ .
[src:segment-tree/fenwick-tree] Each level k of the tree contains nodes with indices corresponding to sums of k distinct powers of 2 (with $k=0$ representing an empty sum 0).
[src:segment-tree/fenwick-tree] To find the prefix sum $A[1]+\cdots +A[i]$ , sum the values in i , its parent, its parent's parent, and so on up to (but not including) the root.
[src:segment-tree/fenwick-tree] To compute a range sum $A[i]+\cdots +A[j]$ , subtract the prefix sums for $i-1$ and j .
[src:segment-tree/fenwick-tree] This can be optimized by stopping at their first common ancestor.
[src:segment-tree/fenwick-tree] An extreme example is asking for a single entry $A[j]$ .
[src:segment-tree/fenwick-tree] In this case, the common ancestor of j and $i=j-1$ is $j-\operatorname {lsb} (j)$ , so start with $F[j]$ and then, as long as $i\neq j-\operatorname {lsb} (j)$ , subtract $F[i]$ and update `i := i - lsb(i)`.
[src:segment-tree/fenwick-tree] The update tree is the mirror image of the interrogation tree.
[src:segment-tree/fenwick-tree] The parent of node i is $i+\operatorname {lsb} (i)=(i\mathbin {|} (i-1))+1$ (where | denotes bitwise OR).
[src:segment-tree/fenwick-tree] This conceptual tree is infinite, but only the part with indexes up to n is stored or used.
[src:segment-tree/fenwick-tree] Excluding the fictitious nodes with indexes greater than n it will be a forest of disjoint trees, one for each bit set in the binary representation of n .
[src:segment-tree/fenwick-tree] Here, a node's ancestors are all nodes whose range sums include its own.
[src:segment-tree/fenwick-tree] To modify one of the values $A[i]$ , add the change to $F[i]$ , then i 's parent, then its grandparent, and so on, until the index exceeds n .
[src:segment-tree/fenwick-tree] Unlike the other two trees, the search tree is a binary tree, arranged in an order Knuth calls a "sideways heap".
[src:segment-tree/fenwick-tree] Each node is assigned a height equal to the number of trailing zeros in the binary representation of its index, with the parent and children being the numerically closest index(es) of the adjacent height.
[src:segment-tree/fenwick-tree] Nodes with odd indexes ( $\operatorname {lsb} (i)=1$ ) are leaves.
[src:segment-tree/fenwick-tree] Nodes with even indexes have the closest two nodes of the next-lowest index as children, $i\pm \operatorname {lsb} (i)/2$ .
[src:segment-tree/fenwick-tree] Node i 's parent in the search tree is $(i-\operatorname {lsb} (i))\mathbin {|} (2\cdot \operatorname {lsb} (i))$ .
[src:segment-tree/fenwick-tree] Although this tree is potentially infinite, we may define its root to be the highest *existing* node, whose index is the greatest power of 2 less than or equal to n .
[src:segment-tree/fenwick-tree] It is possible for a node to have a fictitious parent with an index greater than n yet still have an existing grandparent.
[src:segment-tree/fenwick-tree] If the example above applied to a 5-node tree, then node 5 would have a fictitious parent 6, but an existing grandparent 4.
[src:segment-tree/fenwick-tree] The search tree may be considered a combination of the previous two trees.
[src:segment-tree/fenwick-tree] A node's left subtree contains all of its descendants in the update tree, while its right subtree contains all of its descendants in the interrogation tree.
[src:segment-tree/fenwick-tree] A node's parent in the search tree is either its interrogation or update parent (depending on whether the node is a right or left child, respectively), and the other type of parent may be found by multiple upward steps in the search tree.
[src:segment-tree/fenwick-tree] However, upward traversals in the search tree are uncommon; its primary use is to perform rank queries: given a prefix sum, at what index does it appear?
[src:segment-tree/fenwick-tree] This is done by a *downward* traversal through the search tree.
[src:segment-tree/fenwick-tree] During the traversal, three variables are maintained: The current node's index, the rank being sought in the subtree rooted at the current node, and a "fallback index" to be returned if the rank sought is greater than can be found in the subtree.
[src:segment-tree/fenwick-tree] Initially, the current node is the root, the rank sought is the original query, and the fallback index is a special "overflow" value indicating that the rank is not in the tree.
[src:segment-tree/fenwick-tree] Each step, either the current node is a fictitious node (index greater than n ), or we must decide if the position sought is to the left or right of the end of the current node.
[src:segment-tree/fenwick-tree] If the rank sought is less than the Fenwick array value $F[i]$ for the current node, we must search its left subtree.
[src:segment-tree/fenwick-tree] If it is greater, search its right subtree.
[src:segment-tree/fenwick-tree] If it is equal, the direction chosen depends on how you wish to handle searches for sums lying exactly between two nodes.
[src:segment-tree/fenwick-tree] The function ${\text{lsb}}(n)$ computes the *least significant set bit* of the given n or, equivalently, the largest power of two that is also a divisor of n .
[src:segment-tree/fenwick-tree] This function can be simply implemented in code through a bitwise AND operation: `lsb(n) = n & (-n)`, assuming two's complement negation.
[src:segment-tree/fenwick-tree] One naïve algorithm to construct a Fenwick tree consists of initializing the tree with null values and updating each index individually.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] In computer science, an **interval tree** is a tree data structure to hold intervals.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] Specifically, it allows one to efficiently find all intervals that overlap with any given interval or point.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] It is often used for windowing queries, for instance, to find all roads on a computerized map inside a rectangular viewport, or to find all visible elements inside a three-dimensional scene.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] A similar data structure is the segment tree.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] The trivial solution is to visit each interval and test whether it intersects the given point or interval, which requires $O(n)$ time, where n is the number of intervals in the collection.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] Interval trees have a query time of $O(\log n+m)$ and an initial creation time of $O(n\log n)$ , while limiting memory consumption to $O(n)$ .
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] After creation, interval trees may be dynamic, allowing efficient insertion and deletion of an interval in $O(\log n)$ time.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] If the endpoints of intervals are within a small integer range (*e.g.*, in the range $[1,\ldots ,O(n)]$ ), faster and in fact optimal data structures exist with preprocessing time $O(n)$ and query time $O(1+m)$ for reporting m intervals containing a given query point (see for a very simple one).
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] In a simple case, the intervals do not overlap and they can be inserted into a simple binary search tree and queried in $O(\log n)$ time.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] However, with arbitrarily overlapping intervals, there is no way to compare two intervals for insertion into the tree since orderings sorted by the beginning points or the ending points may be different.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] A naïve approach might be to build two parallel trees, one ordered by the beginning point, and one ordered by the ending point of each interval.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] This allows discarding half of each tree in $O(\log n)$ time, but the results must be merged, requiring $O(n)$ time.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] This returns queries in $O(n+\log n)=O(n)$ , which is no better than brute-force.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] This article describes two alternative designs for an interval tree, dubbed the *centered interval tree* and the *augmented tree*.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] Queries require $O(\log n+m)$ time, with n being the total number of intervals and m being the number of reported results.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] Construction requires $O(n\log n)$ time, and storage requires $O(n)$ space.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] Given a set of n intervals on the number line, a data structure needs to be constructed so that all intervals overlapping another interval or point can be efficiently retrieved.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] First, the entire range of all the intervals is taken and divided in half at $x_{\textrm {center}}$ (in practice, $x_{\textrm {center}}$ should be picked to keep the tree relatively balanced).
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] This gives three sets of intervals, those completely to the left of $x_{\textrm {center}}$ , called $S_{\textrm {left}}$ , those completely to the right of $x_{\textrm {center}}$ , called $S_{\textrm {right}}$ , and those overlapping $x_{\textrm {center}}$ , called $S_{\textrm {center}}$ .
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] The intervals in $S_{\textrm {left}}$ and $S_{\textrm {right}}$ are recursively divided in the same manner until there are no intervals left.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] The intervals in $S_{\textrm {center}}$ that overlap the center point are stored in a separate data structure linked to the node in the interval tree.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] This data structure consists of two lists, one containing all the intervals sorted by their beginning points, and another containing all the intervals sorted by their ending points.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] Interval trees allow for quickly computing all the ranges overlapping any input.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] The task is to find all intervals in the tree that overlap a given point x .
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] The tree is walked with a similar recursive algorithm as would be used to traverse a traditional binary tree, but with extra logic to support searching the intervals overlapping the "center" point at each node.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] For each tree node, x is compared to $x_{\textrm {center}}$ , the midpoint used in node construction above.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] If x is less than $x_{\textrm {center}}$ , the leftmost set of intervals, $S_{\textrm {left}}$ , is considered.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] If x is greater than $x_{\textrm {center}}$ , the rightmost set of intervals, $S_{\textrm {right}}$ , is considered.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] As each node is processed as the tree is traversed from the root to a leaf, the ranges in its $S_{\textrm {center}}$ are processed.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] If x is less than $x_{\textrm {center}}$ , all intervals in $S_{\textrm {center}}$ must end after x , or they could not also overlap $x_{\textrm {center}}$ .
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] Therefore, it is only necessary find those intervals in $S_{\textrm {center}}$ that begin before x .
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] The lists of $S_{\textrm {center}}$ , which have already been constructed, can be consulted.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] Since only the interval beginnings are relevant in this scenario, the list can be sorted by beginnings.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] If the closest number no greater than x is found in this list, all ranges from the beginning of the list to that found point overlap x because they begin before x and end after x (because they overlap $x_{\textrm {center}}$ which is larger than x ).
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] Thus, the intervals in the list can be enumerated until the startpoint value exceeds x .
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] Likewise, if x is greater than $x_{\textrm {center}}$ , all intervals in $S_{\textrm {center}}$ must begin before x , so the intervals that end after x can be found using the list sorted by interval endings.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] If x exactly matches $x_{\textrm {center}}$ , all intervals in $S_{\textrm {center}}$ can be added to the results without further processing and tree traversal can be stopped.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] We first find all intervals with start and/or end points inside q using a separately-constructed tree.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] In the one-dimensional case, we can use a search tree containing all the start and end points in the interval set, each with a pointer to its corresponding interval.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] A binary search in $O(\log n)$ time for the start and end of q reveals the minimum and maximum points to consider.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] Each point within this range references an interval that overlaps q and is added to the result list.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] Care must be taken to avoid duplicates, since an interval might both begin and end within q .
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] This can be done using a binary flag on each interval to mark whether or not it has been added to the result set.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] Finally, we must find intervals that enclose q .
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] To find these, we pick any point inside q and use the algorithm above to find all intervals intersecting that point (again, being careful to remove duplicates).
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] The interval tree data structure can be generalized to a higher dimension N with identical query and construction time and $O(n\log n)$ space.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] First, a range tree in N dimensions is constructed that allows efficient retrieval of all intervals with beginning and end points inside the query region R .
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] Once the corresponding ranges are found, the only thing that is left are those ranges that enclose the region in some dimension.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] To find these overlaps, N interval trees are created, and one axis intersecting R is queried for each.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] For example, in two dimensions, the bottom of the square R (or any other horizontal line intersecting R ) would be queried against the interval tree constructed for the horizontal axis.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] Likewise, the left (or any other vertical line intersecting R ) would be queried against the interval tree constructed on the vertical axis.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] Each interval tree also needs an addition for higher dimensions.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] At each node we traverse in the tree, x is compared with $S_{\textrm {center}}$ to find overlaps.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] Instead of two sorted lists of points as was used in the one-dimensional case, a range tree is constructed.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] This allows efficient retrieval of all points in $S_{\textrm {center}}$ that overlap region R .
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] If after deleting an interval from the tree, the node containing that interval contains no more intervals, that node may be deleted from the tree.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] This is more complex than a normal binary tree deletion operation.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] An interval may overlap the center point of several nodes in the tree.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] Since each node stores the intervals that overlap it, with all intervals completely to the left of its center point in the left subtree, similarly for the right subtree, it follows that each interval is stored in the node closest to the root from the set of nodes whose center point it overlaps.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] Normal deletion operations in a binary tree (for the case where the node being deleted has two children) involve promoting a node further from the leaf to the position of the node being deleted (usually the leftmost child of the right subtree, or the rightmost child of the left subtree).
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] As a result of this promotion, some nodes that were above the promoted node will become its descendants; it is necessary to search these nodes for intervals that also overlap the promoted node, and move those intervals into the promoted node.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] As a consequence, this may result in new empty nodes, which must be deleted, following the same algorithm again.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] The same issues that affect deletion also affect rotation operations; rotation must preserve the invariant that nodes are stored as close to the root as possible.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] Another way to represent intervals is described in Cormen et al.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] Both insertion and deletion require $O(\log n)$ time, with n being the total number of intervals in the tree prior to the insertion or deletion operation.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] An augmented tree can be built from a simple ordered tree, for example a binary search tree or self-balancing binary search tree, ordered by the 'low' values of the intervals.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] An extra annotation is then added to every node, recording the maximum upper value among all the intervals from this node down.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] Maintaining this attribute involves updating all ancestors of the node from the bottom up whenever a node is added or deleted.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] This takes only O(*h*) steps per node addition or removal, where *h* is the height of the node added or removed in the tree.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] If there are any tree rotations during insertion and deletion, the affected nodes may need updating as well.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] Now, it is known that two intervals A and B overlap only when both $A_{\textrm {low}}\leq B_{\textrm {high}}$ and $A_{\textrm {high}}\geq B_{\textrm {low}}$ .
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] Some performance may be gained if the tree avoids unnecessary traversals.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] These can occur when adding intervals that already exist or removing intervals that don't exist.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] A total order can be defined on the intervals by ordering them first by their lower bounds and then by their upper bounds.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] Then, a membership check can be performed in $O(\log n)$ time, versus the $O(k+\log n)$ time required to find duplicates if k intervals overlap the interval to be inserted or removed.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] This solution has the advantage of not requiring any additional structures.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] The disadvantage is that membership queries take $O(\log n)$ time.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] Alternately, at the rate of $O(n)$ memory, membership queries in expected constant time can be implemented with a hash table, updated in lockstep with the interval tree.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] This may not necessarily double the total memory requirement, if the intervals are stored by reference rather than by value.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] To search for an interval, one walks the tree, using the key (`n.getKey()`) and high value (`n.getValue()`) to omit any branches that cannot overlap the query.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] Augmented trees can be extended to higher dimensions by cycling through the dimensions at each level of the tree.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] For example, for two dimensions, the odd levels of the tree might contain ranges for the *x*-coordinate, while the even levels contain ranges for the *y*-coordinate.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] This approach effectively converts the data structure from an augmented binary tree to an augmented kd-tree, thus significantly complicating the balancing algorithms for insertions and deletions.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] A simpler solution is to use nested interval trees.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] First, create a tree using the ranges for the *y*-coordinate.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] Now, for each node in the tree, add another interval tree on the *x*-ranges, for all elements whose *y*-range is the same as that node's *y*-range.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] The advantage of this solution is that it can be extended to an arbitrary number of dimensions using the same code base.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] At first, the additional cost of the nested trees might seem prohibitive, but this is usually not so.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] As with the non-nested solution earlier, one node is needed per *x*-coordinate, yielding the same number of nodes for both solutions.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] The only additional overhead is that of the nested tree structures, one per vertical interval.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] This structure is usually of negligible size, consisting only of a pointer to the root node, and possibly the number of nodes and the depth of the tree.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] A medial- or length-oriented tree is similar to an augmented tree, but symmetrical, with the binary search tree ordered by the medial points of the intervals.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] There is a maximum-oriented binary heap in every node, ordered by the length of the interval (or half of the length).
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] Also we store the minimum and maximum possible value of the subtree in each node (thus the symmetry).
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] Adding new intervals to the tree is the same as for a binary search tree using the medial value as the key.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] We push $d_{i}$ onto the binary heap associated with the node, and update the minimum and maximum possible values associated with all higher nodes.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] Starting with root node, in each node, first we check if it is possible that our query interval overlaps with the node subtree using minimum and maximum values of node (if it is not, we don't continue for this node).
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] Then we pass through both left and right children of the node, doing the same thing.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] This algorithm is expected to be faster than a traditional interval tree (augmented tree) for search operations.
[src:segment-tree/interval-tree] Adding elements is a little slower in practice, though the order of growth is the same.
[src:segment-tree/priority-search-tree] In computer science, a **priority search tree** is a tree data structure for storing points in two dimensions.
[src:segment-tree/priority-search-tree] It was originally introduced by Edward M.
[src:segment-tree/priority-search-tree] It is effectively an extension of the priority queue with the purpose of improving the search time from O(*n*) to O(*s* + log *n*) time, where *n* is the number of points in the tree and *s* is the number of points returned by the search.
[src:segment-tree/priority-search-tree] The priority search tree is used to store a set of 2-dimensional points ordered by priority and by a key value.
[src:segment-tree/priority-search-tree] This is accomplished by creating a hybrid of a priority queue and a binary search tree.
[src:segment-tree/priority-search-tree] The result is a tree where each node represents a point in the original dataset.
[src:segment-tree/priority-search-tree] The point contained by the node is the one with the lowest priority.
[src:segment-tree/priority-search-tree] In addition, each node also contains a key value used to divide the remaining points (usually the median of the keys, excluding the point of the node) into a left and right subtree.
[src:segment-tree/priority-search-tree] The points are divided by comparing their key values to the node key, delegating the ones with lower keys to the left subtree, and the ones strictly greater to the right subtree.
[src:segment-tree/priority-search-tree] The construction of the tree requires O(*n* log *n*) time and O(*n*) space.
[src:segment-tree/priority-search-tree] However, if the points are sorted by their key values then the tree can be constructed in linear time.
[src:segment-tree/priority-search-tree] This can easily be done by constructing a balanced binary tree over the key values (as leaves) in linear time.
[src:segment-tree/priority-search-tree] Each internal node stores a pointer to the lowest priority node and count of number of items in the subtree rooted at that node.
[src:segment-tree/priority-search-tree] Thus, the node with minimum priority can be identified in constant time.
[src:segment-tree/priority-search-tree] The median of remaining points and the item with next smallest priority can be identified in O(log n) time.
[src:segment-tree/priority-search-tree] Thus, the recurrence relation is T(n)=2T(n/2)+O(log n)=O(n).
[src:segment-tree/priority-search-tree] The priority search tree can be efficiently queried for a key in a closed interval and for a maximum priority value.
[src:segment-tree/priority-search-tree] That is, one can specify an interval [*min_key*, *max_key*] and another interval [-∞, *max_priority*] and return the points contained within it.
[src:segment-tree/range-minimum-query] In computer science, a **range minimum query** (**RMQ**) solves the problem of finding the minimal value in a sub-array of an array of comparable objects.
[src:segment-tree/range-minimum-query] Range minimum queries have several use cases in computer science, such as the lowest common ancestor problem and the longest common prefix problem (LCP).
[src:segment-tree/range-minimum-query] Given an array *A*[1 … *n*] of n objects taken from a totally ordered set, such as integers, the range minimum query RMQ*A*(*l*,*r*) =arg min *A*[*k*] (with 1 ≤ *l* ≤ *k* ≤ *r* ≤ *n*) returns the position of the minimal element in the specified sub-array *A*[*l* … *r*].
[src:segment-tree/range-minimum-query] In a typical setting, the array A is static, i.e., elements are not inserted or deleted during a series of queries, and the queries to be answered on-line (i.e., the whole set of queries are not known in advance to the algorithm).
[src:segment-tree/range-minimum-query] In this case a suitable preprocessing of the array into a data structure ensures faster query answering.
[src:segment-tree/range-minimum-query] A naive solution is to precompute all possible queries, i.e. the minimum of all sub-arrays of A, and store these in an array B such that *B*[*i*, *j*] = min(*A*[*i*…*j*]); then a range min query can be solved in constant time by array lookup in B.
[src:segment-tree/range-minimum-query] There are Θ(*n*²) possible queries for a length-n array, and the answers to these can be computed in Θ(*n*²) time by dynamic programming.
[src:segment-tree/range-minimum-query] As in the solution above, answering queries in constant time will be achieved by pre-computing results.
[src:segment-tree/range-minimum-query] However, the array will store pre-computed range minimum queries not for every range [*i*, *j*], but only for ranges whose size is a power of two.
[src:segment-tree/range-minimum-query] There are O(log *n*) such queries for each start position i, so the size of the dynamic programming table B is O(*n* log *n*).
[src:segment-tree/range-minimum-query] After this pre-computing step, a query RMQ*A*(*l*,*r*) can now be answered in constant time by splitting it into two separate queries: one is the pre-computed query with range from l to the largest memoized value smaller than r.
[src:segment-tree/range-minimum-query] The other is the query of an interval of the same length that has r as its right boundary.
[src:segment-tree/range-minimum-query] These intervals may overlap, but since we are trying to compute the minimum rather than, for example, the sum of the numbers in the array, this does not matter.
[src:segment-tree/range-minimum-query] The overall result can thus be obtained, after the linearithmic time pre-computing, in constant time: the two queries can be answered in constant time and the only thing left to do is to choose the smaller of the two results.
[src:segment-tree/range-minimum-query] This solution does pre-computation in *O*(*n*) time.
[src:segment-tree/range-minimum-query] Its data structures use *O*(*n*) space and its data structures can be used to answer queries in logarithmic time.
[src:segment-tree/range-minimum-query] The array is first conceptually divided into blocks of size *s* = ⁠log *n*/4⁠.
[src:segment-tree/range-minimum-query] Then the minimum for each block can be computed in *O*(*n*) time overall and the minima are stored in a new array.
[src:segment-tree/range-minimum-query] For example, using the array *A* = [0,5,2,5,4,3,1,6,3] and a block size of 3 (for illustrative purposes only) yields the minimum array *A'* = [0,3,1].
[src:segment-tree/range-minimum-query] Using the solution above, the sub-queries inside the blocks that are not fully contained in the query still need to be answered in constant time.
[src:segment-tree/range-minimum-query] There are at most two of those blocks: the block containing l and the block containing r.
[src:segment-tree/range-minimum-query] Constant time is achieved by storing the Cartesian trees for all the blocks in the array.
[src:segment-tree/range-minimum-query] For every such tree, the possible result for all queries need to be stored.
[src:segment-tree/range-minimum-query] This comes down to *s*2 or *O*(log2 *n*) entries.
[src:segment-tree/range-minimum-query] This means the overall size of the table is *O*(*n*).
[src:segment-tree/range-minimum-query] To look up results efficiently, the Cartesian tree (row) corresponding to a specific block must be addressable in constant time.
[src:segment-tree/range-minimum-query] The solution is to store the results for all trees in an array and find a unique projection from binary trees to integers to address the entries.
[src:segment-tree/range-minimum-query] This can be achieved by doing a breadth-first-search through the tree and adding leaf nodes so that every existing node in the Cartesian tree has exactly two children.
[src:segment-tree/range-minimum-query] The integer is then generated by representing every inner node as a 0-bit and every leaf as a 1-bit in a bit-word (by traversing the tree in level-order again).
[src:segment-tree/range-minimum-query] This leads to a size of ⁠log *n*/4⁠ for every tree.
[src:segment-tree/range-minimum-query] To enable random access in constant time to any tree, the trees not contained in the original array need to be included as well.
[src:segment-tree/range-minimum-query] An array with indices of ⁠log *n*/4⁠ bits length has size 2⁠log *n*/4⁠ = *O*(*n*).
[src:segment-tree/range-minimum-query] RMQs are used as a tool for many tasks in exact and approximate string matching.
[src:segment-tree/range-minimum-query] Several applications can be found in Fischer and Heun (2007).
[src:segment-tree/range-minimum-query] RMQs can be used to solve the lowest common ancestor problem and are used as a tool for many tasks in exact and approximate string matching.
[src:segment-tree/range-minimum-query] The LCA query LCA*S*(*v*, *w*) of a rooted tree *S* = (*V*, *E*) and two nodes *v*, *w* ∈ *V* returns the deepest node u (which may be v or w) on paths from the root to both w and v.
[src:segment-tree/range-minimum-query] Gabow, Bentley, and Tarjan (1984) showed that the LCA Problem can be reduced in linear time to the RMQ problem.
[src:segment-tree/range-minimum-query] It follows that, like the RMQ problem, the LCA problem can be solved in constant time and linear space.
[src:segment-tree/range-minimum-query] In the context of text indexing, RMQs can be used to find the LCP (longest common prefix), where LCP*T*(*i*, *j*) computes the LCP of the suffixes that start at indexes i and j in T.
[src:segment-tree/range-minimum-query] To do this we first compute the suffix array A, and the inverse suffix array *A*−1.
[src:segment-tree/range-minimum-query] We then compute the LCP array H giving the LCP of adjacent suffixes in A.
[src:segment-tree/range-minimum-query] Once these data structures are computed, and RMQ preprocessing is complete, the length of the general LCP can be computed in constant time by the formula: LCP(*i*, *j*) = RMQH(*A*-1[*i*] + 1, *A*-1[*j*]), where we assume for simplicity that *A*-1[*i*] + 1 <= *A*-1[*j*] (otherwise swap).
[src:segment-tree/range-tree] In computer science, a **range tree** is an ordered tree data structure to hold a list of points.
[src:segment-tree/range-tree] It allows all points within a given range to be reported efficiently, and is typically used in two or higher dimensions.
[src:segment-tree/range-tree] Range trees were introduced by Jon Louis Bentley in 1979.
[src:segment-tree/range-tree] Similar data structures were discovered independently by Lueker, Lee and Wong, and Willard.
[src:segment-tree/range-tree] The range tree is an alternative to the *k*-d tree.
[src:segment-tree/range-tree] Compared to *k*-d trees, range trees offer faster query times of (in Big O notation) $O(\log ^{d}n+k)$ but worse storage of $O(n\log ^{d-1}n)$ , where *n* is the number of points stored in the tree, *d* is the dimension of each point and *k* is the number of points reported by a given query.
[src:segment-tree/range-tree] In 1990, Bernard Chazelle improved this to query time $O(\log ^{d-1}n+k)$ and space complexity $O\left(n\left({\frac {\log n}{\log \log n}}\right)^{d-1}\right)$ .
[src:segment-tree/range-tree] A range tree on a set of 1-dimensional points is a balanced binary search tree on those points.
[src:segment-tree/range-tree] The points stored in the tree are stored in the leaves of the tree; each internal node stores the largest value of its left subtree.
[src:segment-tree/range-tree] A range tree on a set of points in *d*-dimensions is a recursively defined multi-level binary search tree.
[src:segment-tree/range-tree] Each level of the data structure is a binary search tree on one of the *d*-dimensions.
[src:segment-tree/range-tree] The first level is a binary search tree on the first of the *d*-coordinates.
[src:segment-tree/range-tree] Each vertex *v* of this tree contains an associated structure that is a (*d*−1)-dimensional range tree on the last (*d*−1)-coordinates of the points stored in the subtree of *v*.
[src:segment-tree/range-tree] A 1-dimensional range tree on a set of *n* points is a binary search tree, which can be constructed in $O(n\log n)$ time.
[src:segment-tree/range-tree] Range trees in higher dimensions are constructed recursively by constructing a balanced binary search tree on the first coordinate of the points, and then, for each vertex *v* in this tree, constructing a (*d*−1)-dimensional range tree on the points contained in the subtree of *v*.
[src:segment-tree/range-tree] Constructing a range tree this way would require $O(n\log ^{d}n)$ time.
[src:segment-tree/range-tree] This construction time can be improved for 2-dimensional range trees to $O(n\log n)$ .
[src:segment-tree/range-tree] Let *S* be a set of *n* 2-dimensional points.
[src:segment-tree/range-tree] If *S* contains only one point, return a leaf containing that point.
[src:segment-tree/range-tree] Otherwise, construct the associated structure of *S*, a 1-dimensional range tree on the *y*-coordinates of the points in *S*.
[src:segment-tree/range-tree] Let *x*m be the median *x*-coordinate of the points.
[src:segment-tree/range-tree] Let *S*L be the set of points with *x*-coordinate less than or equal to *x*m and let *S*R be the set of points with *x*-coordinate greater than *x*m.
[src:segment-tree/range-tree] Recursively construct *v*L, a 2-dimensional range tree on *S*L, and *v*R, a 2-dimensional range tree on *S*R.
[src:segment-tree/range-tree] Create a vertex *v* with left-child *v*L and right-child *v*R.
[src:segment-tree/range-tree] If we sort the points by their *y*-coordinates at the start of the algorithm, and maintain this ordering when splitting the points by their *x*-coordinate, we can construct the associated structures of each subtree in linear time.
[src:segment-tree/range-tree] This reduces the time to construct a 2-dimensional range tree to $O(n\log n)$ , and also reduces the time to construct a *d*-dimensional range tree to $O(n\log ^{d-1}n)$ .
[src:segment-tree/range-tree] A range query on a range tree reports the set of points that lie inside a given interval.
[src:segment-tree/range-tree] To report the points that lie in the interval [*x*1, *x*2], we start by searching for *x*1 and *x*2.
[src:segment-tree/range-tree] At some vertex in the tree, the search paths to *x*1 and *x*2 will diverge.
[src:segment-tree/range-tree] Let *v*split be the last vertex that these two search paths have in common.
[src:segment-tree/range-tree] For every vertex *v* in the search path from *v*split to *x*1, if the value stored at *v* is greater than *x*1, report every point in the right-subtree of *v*.
[src:segment-tree/range-tree] If *v* is a leaf, report the value stored at *v* if it is inside the query interval.
[src:segment-tree/range-tree] Similarly, reporting all of the points stored in the left-subtrees of the vertices with values less than *x*2 along the search path from *v*split to *x*2, and report the leaf of this path if it lies within the query interval.
[src:segment-tree/range-tree] Since the range tree is a balanced binary tree, the search paths to *x*1 and *x*2 have length $O(\log n)$ .
[src:segment-tree/range-tree] Reporting all of the points stored in the subtree of a vertex can be done in linear time using any tree traversal algorithm.
[src:segment-tree/range-tree] It follows that the time to perform a range query is $O(\log n+k)$ , where *k* is the number of points in the query interval.
[src:segment-tree/range-tree] Range queries in *d*-dimensions are similar.
[src:segment-tree/range-tree] Instead of reporting all of the points stored in the subtrees of the search paths, perform a (*d*−1)-dimensional range query on the associated structure of each subtree.
[src:segment-tree/range-tree] Eventually, a 1-dimensional range query will be performed and the correct points will be reported.
[src:segment-tree/range-tree] Since a *d*-dimensional query consists of $O(\log n)$ (*d*−1)-dimensional range queries, it follows that the time required to perform a *d*-dimensional range query is $O(\log ^{d}n+k)$ , where *k* is the number of points in the query interval.
[src:segment-tree/range-tree] This can be reduced to $O(\log ^{d-1}n+k)$ using a variant of fractional cascading.
[src:segment-tree/segment-tree] In computer science, the **segment tree** is a data structure used for storing information about intervals or segments.
[src:segment-tree/segment-tree] It allows querying which of the stored segments contain a given point.
[src:segment-tree/segment-tree] A similar data structure is the interval tree.
[src:segment-tree/segment-tree] A segment tree for a set I of *n* intervals uses *O*(*n* log *n*) storage and can be built in *O*(*n* log *n*) time.
[src:segment-tree/segment-tree] Segment trees support searching for all the intervals that contain a query point in time *O*(log *n* + *k*), *k* being the number of retrieved intervals or segments.
[src:segment-tree/segment-tree] Applications of the segment tree are in the areas of computational geometry, geographic information systems and machine learning.
[src:segment-tree/segment-tree] The segment tree can be generalized to higher dimension spaces.
[src:segment-tree/segment-tree] Let I be a set of intervals, or segments.
[src:segment-tree/segment-tree] Let *p*1, *p*2, ..., *pm* be the list of distinct interval endpoints, sorted from left to right.
[src:segment-tree/segment-tree] Consider the partitioning of the real line induced by those points.
[src:segment-tree/segment-tree] The regions of this partitioning are called *elementary intervals*.
[src:segment-tree/segment-tree] That is, the list of elementary intervals consists of open intervals between two consecutive endpoints *pi* and *p**i*+1, alternated with closed intervals consisting of a single endpoint.
[src:segment-tree/segment-tree] Single points are treated themselves as intervals because the answer to a query is not necessarily the same at the interior of an elementary interval and its endpoints.
[src:segment-tree/segment-tree] A segment tree from the set of segments I, can be built as follows.
[src:segment-tree/segment-tree] First, the endpoints of the intervals in I are sorted.
[src:segment-tree/segment-tree] The elementary intervals are obtained from that.
[src:segment-tree/segment-tree] Then, a balanced binary tree is built on the elementary intervals, and for each node *v* it is determined the interval Int(*v*) it represents.
[src:segment-tree/segment-tree] It remains to compute the canonical subsets for the nodes.
[src:segment-tree/segment-tree] To achieve this, the intervals in I are inserted one by one into the segment tree.
[src:segment-tree/segment-tree] The complete construction operation takes *O*(*n* log *n*) time, *n* being the number of segments in I.
[src:segment-tree/segment-tree] Visiting every node takes constant time (assuming that canonical subsets are stored in a simple data structure like a linked list).
[src:segment-tree/segment-tree] When we visit node *v*, we either store *X* at *v*, or Int(*v*) contains an endpoint of *X*.
[src:segment-tree/segment-tree] As proved above, an interval is stored at most twice at each level of the tree.
[src:segment-tree/segment-tree] There is also at most one node at every level whose corresponding interval contains *x*, and one node whose interval contains *x′*.
[src:segment-tree/segment-tree] So, at most four nodes per level are visited.
[src:segment-tree/segment-tree] Since there are *O*(log *n*) levels, the total cost of the insertion is *O*(log *n*).
[src:segment-tree/segment-tree] A query for a segment tree receives a point *qx*(should be one of the leaves of tree), and retrieves a list of all the segments stored which contain the point *qx*.
[src:segment-tree/segment-tree] In a segment tree that contains *n* intervals, those containing a given query point can be reported in *O*(log *n* + *k*) time, where *k* is the number of reported intervals.
[src:segment-tree/segment-tree] The query algorithm visits one node per level of the tree, so *O*(log *n*) nodes in total.
[src:segment-tree/segment-tree] On the other hand, at a node *v*, the segments in I are reported in *O*(1 + *kv*) time, where *kv* is the number of intervals at node *v*, reported.
[src:segment-tree/segment-tree] The sum of all the *kv* for all nodes *v* visited, is *k*, the number of reported segments.
[src:segment-tree/segment-tree] A segment tree *T* on a set I of *n* intervals uses *O*(*n* log *n*) storage.
[src:segment-tree/segment-tree] Let *v*1, *v*2, *v*3 be the three nodes at the same depth, numbered from left to right; and let p(*v*) be the parent node of any given node *v*.
[src:segment-tree/segment-tree] This means that [*x*, *x′*] spans the whole interval from the left endpoint of Int(*v*1) to the right endpoint of Int(*v*3).
[src:segment-tree/segment-tree] Note that all segments at a particular level are non-overlapping and ordered from left to right: this is true by construction for the level containing the leaves, and the property is not lost when moving from any level to the one above it by combining pairs of adjacent segments.
[src:segment-tree/segment-tree] Now either parent(*v*2) = parent(*v*1), or the former is to the right of the latter (edges in the tree do not cross).
[src:segment-tree/segment-tree] In the first case, Int(parent(*v*2))'s leftmost point is the same as Int(*v*1)'s leftmost point; in the second case, Int(parent(*v*2))'s leftmost point is to the right of Int(parent(*v*1))'s rightmost point, and therefore also to the right of Int(*v*1)'s rightmost point.
[src:segment-tree/segment-tree] In both cases, Int(parent(*v*2)) begins at or to the right of Int(*v*1)'s leftmost point.
[src:segment-tree/segment-tree] Similar reasoning shows that Int(parent(*v*2)) ends at or to the left of Int(*v*3)'s rightmost point.
[src:segment-tree/segment-tree] Int(parent(*v*2)) must therefore be contained in [*x*, *x′*]; hence, [*x*, *x′*] will not be stored at *v*2.
[src:segment-tree/segment-tree] The segment tree can be generalized to higher dimension spaces, in the form of multi-level segment trees.
[src:segment-tree/segment-tree] In higher dimensional versions, the segment tree stores a collection of axis-parallel (hyper-)rectangles, and can retrieve the rectangles that contain a given query point.
[src:segment-tree/segment-tree] The structure uses *O*(*n* log*d* *n*) storage, and answers queries in *O*(log*d* *n*) time.
[src:segment-tree/segment-tree] The use of fractional cascading lowers the query time bound by a logarithmic factor.
[src:segment-tree/segment-tree] The use of the interval tree on the deepest level of associated structures lowers the storage bound by a logarithmic factor.
